  <h1>Jeddah Expat Guide 2026: Salaries, Cost of Living, and Lifestyle</h1>

  <p>Jeddah is Saudi Arabia's second-largest city and its most cosmopolitan, with a rich trading history, Red Sea coastline, and a more relaxed social atmosphere than the capital. Known as the gateway to the holy cities of Makkah and Madinah, Jeddah has long hosted a diverse international community spanning Arab, South Asian, Southeast Asian, and Western nationalities. In 2026, the city benefits from Vision 2030 investments in tourism, waterfront development, and cultural heritage, while maintaining its traditional role as Saudi Arabia's commercial and logistics hub. With a population exceeding 4.5 million, Jeddah blends ancient Hejazi traditions with rapid modernization, making it one of the most rewarding Gulf cities for expatriates who value cultural depth alongside professional opportunity.</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-8"><CostOfLivingSimulator client:idle defaultCity="jeddah" /></div>

  <h2>Jeddah Salary Overview</h2>
  <p>Jeddah salaries average SAR 11,000 (~€2,640) per month, making it somewhat lower than Riyadh. The city's strongest sectors include logistics and maritime operations through Jeddah Islamic Port, healthcare at major hospitals like King Faisal Specialist Hospital and Dr. Soliman Fakeeh Hospital, and the growing tourism and hospitality sector driven by Red Sea tourism development. Engineering and project management roles pay SAR 12,000-25,000 (~€2,880-6,000), while healthcare professionals earn SAR 10,000-35,000 (~€2,400-8,400) depending on specialty. The retail and F&B sectors, boosted by new mall developments and waterfront dining, employ many international professionals. All salaries are tax-free, and employer packages typically include housing allowance, flights, and health insurance.</p>
  <p>Specific salary benchmarks for popular Jeddah roles in 2026 include: logistics and supply chain managers at SAR 14,000-22,000 (~€3,360-5,280), hospitality general managers at SAR 18,000-30,000 (~€4,320-7,200), nurses at SAR 7,000-12,000 (~€1,680-2,880), IT professionals at SAR 12,000-20,000 (~€2,880-4,800), and teachers at international schools at SAR 8,000-14,000 (~€1,920-3,360). The Red Sea Global tourism mega-project, while based north of Jeddah, has its project management offices in the city, creating demand for urban planning, environmental management, and hospitality development professionals at SAR 15,000-35,000 (~€3,600-8,400). Port and customs operations at Jeddah Islamic Port employ a large international workforce in freight forwarding, customs brokerage, and warehousing at SAR 8,000-18,000 (~€1,920-4,320).</p>

  <CostOfLivingBreakdown city="Jeddah" country="saudi-arabia" />

  <h2>Cost of Living in Jeddah</h2>
  <p>Jeddah is slightly cheaper than Riyadh, particularly for housing. A one-bedroom apartment in central areas like Al Rawdah or Al Hamra costs SAR 2,000-4,000 (~€480-960). The Corniche and waterfront areas are pricier at SAR 3,500-5,500 (~€840-1,320). Family villas in compound communities run SAR 6,000-15,000 (~€1,440-3,600). Groceries cost SAR 750-1,600 (~€180-384) per month at Danube, LuLu, or Tamimi Markets. Dining ranges from SAR 15 (~€4) at casual restaurants to SAR 120 (~€29) at mid-range venues. The 15% VAT applies to all taxable goods. <a href="/saudi-arabia/utilities/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Utilities</a> are subsidized, averaging SAR 250-700 (~€60-168) monthly. A single professional can live comfortably on SAR 5,000-7,500 (~€1,200-1,800), while families should budget SAR 10,000-20,000 (~€2,400-4,800).</p>
  <p>Jeddah's food scene is affordable for daily eating. A shawarma or falafel sandwich costs SAR 8-15 (~€2-4), a coffee at a specialty cafe runs SAR 18-28 (~€4-7), and a meal at one of the upscale Corniche restaurants averages SAR 120-200 (~€29-48) per person. Friday brunch, a popular social tradition, ranges from SAR 80-180 (~€19-43) at hotel restaurants. Monthly gym memberships cost SAR 150-400 (~€36-96), with premium fitness clubs like Fitness Time and Gold's Gym at the higher end. Cinema tickets average SAR 55-75 (~€13-18). For families, nursery fees range from SAR 15,000-35,000 (~€3,600-8,400) per year, while <a href="/saudi-arabia/education/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">international school</a> tuition runs SAR 20,000-60,000 (~€4,800-14,400) annually depending on the curriculum and school tier.</p>

  <h2>Neighborhoods and Housing</h2>
  <p>Jeddah's residential landscape is diverse, and choosing the right neighborhood depends on your work location, family needs, and budget. Al Rawdah and Al Hamra offer central apartment living with access to shopping malls like Red Sea Mall and dining. The Corniche area provides waterfront proximity at premium prices, with newer high-rise buildings offering sea views. Al Shati (North Obhur) offers beachside villas and compound living, particularly popular with families who want access to beach clubs and water sports. Compound communities like the Saudi Arabian Parsons compound and various gated communities are popular with Western expat families, offering swimming pools, tennis courts, and social facilities within secure environments. Al Andalus and Al Salamah are mid-range family areas with good access to schools and supermarkets. The new Jeddah Tower development area and waterfront projects are creating modern residential options.</p>
  <p>For budget-conscious expats, areas like Al Safa, Al Marwah, and Al Faisaliyah provide more affordable apartments at SAR 1,500-2,500 (~€360-600) per month, though these neighborhoods tend to be noisier and less manicured than premium areas. The northern stretch of Jeddah along Prince Sultan Road has emerged as a lifestyle corridor with cafes, boutiques, and modern apartments. Obhur, further north, offers a quieter residential environment with access to beach resorts and boat marinas, making it ideal for water sports enthusiasts. Rent in Jeddah is typically paid in two to four installments per year via post-dated checks, though some landlords now accept monthly bank transfers. Security deposits are usually equivalent to one month's rent.</p>

  <h2>Commuting and Transportation</h2>
  <p>Jeddah does not yet have a metro system, though the Haramain High-Speed Railway connects Jeddah to Makkah and Madinah, which is useful for weekend trips rather than daily commuting. Within the city, most expats rely on private cars or ride-hailing through Uber and Careem. Traffic can be heavy during peak hours, particularly on Madinah Road, Palestine Street, and the Corniche during weekends. A typical commute from Al Shati to the city center takes 25-40 minutes outside rush hour and up to 60 minutes during peak times. Parking is generally easier and cheaper than in Riyadh or Dubai, with free street parking available in many residential areas. Petrol is inexpensive at approximately SAR 2.18 (~€0.52) per liter for 91 octane. Car rental starts from SAR 1,500 (~€360) per month for a basic sedan, while purchasing a used car costs SAR 25,000-60,000 (~€6,000-14,400) for a reliable model. The Saptco bus network operates limited routes across the city, but service frequency and coverage are not yet sufficient for most expat commuting needs.</p>

  <h2>Working in Jeddah</h2>
  <p>Jeddah's economy centers on trade, logistics, healthcare, and increasingly tourism. Jeddah Islamic Port handles 65% of Saudi imports, making shipping and logistics the backbone of the local economy. The Red Sea tourism project, about 500 km north, creates opportunities accessible from Jeddah. Healthcare is a major employer with Saudi German Hospitals, International Medical Center, and government hospitals recruiting international staff. The Hajj and Umrah industry supports hospitality, transport, and services sectors year-round but peaks sharply during pilgrimage seasons. The creative and arts scene is growing, with events and galleries in the historic Al-Balad district. Jeddah also serves as the regional headquarters for several multinational companies operating in western Saudi Arabia.</p>
  <p>The standard work week is Sunday to Thursday, with Friday and Saturday as the weekend. Government offices follow this schedule, while some international companies have shifted to a Monday-to-Friday pattern. Working hours during Ramadan are reduced to six hours per day by law. Saudization (Nitaqat) requirements apply to all private sector employers, meaning companies must maintain minimum quotas of Saudi employees. However, specialist roles in engineering, healthcare, IT, and senior management remain open to international professionals. Networking is important in Jeddah's business culture, and professional events hosted by the Jeddah Chamber of Commerce and industry associations provide valuable connection opportunities.</p>

  <h2>Schools and Education</h2>
  <p>Jeddah has a solid network of international schools serving the expat community. The British International School of Jeddah (BISJ) and Jeddah Knowledge International School offer British curriculum education with strong KHDA-equivalent inspection results. The American International School of Jeddah follows a US curriculum with AP courses. For IB programs, several schools offer the International Baccalaureate alongside their primary curriculum. Indian-curriculum schools including Jeddah International Indian School and International Indian School Jeddah provide affordable education at SAR 8,000-15,000 (~€1,920-3,600) per year. Pakistani and Bangladeshi community schools also operate in the city. School transport is widely available but costs SAR 3,000-6,000 (~€720-1,440) per year per child. Most international schools in Jeddah are located in the northern part of the city, so families choosing schools should factor in commute times when selecting housing.</p>

  <h2>Healthcare Facilities</h2>
  <p>Jeddah has comprehensive healthcare options for expatriates. King Faisal Specialist Hospital and Research Centre (KFSHRC) is one of the region's most advanced medical facilities, offering tertiary care and specialized treatments. Dr. Soliman Fakeeh Hospital is the largest private hospital in western Saudi Arabia, with over 700 beds and a full range of specialties. Saudi German Hospital Jeddah provides affordable private care popular with expat families. International Medical Center (IMC) is a well-regarded multi-specialty hospital in the Andalusia area. For everyday primary care, Nahdi Medical clinics and various polyclinics offer GP consultations at SAR 100-250 (~€24-60). Dental care is widely available, with routine check-ups costing SAR 150-300 (~€36-72). All employers are legally required to provide CCHI-approved <a href="/saudi-arabia/healthcare/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">health insurance</a>, which typically covers hospital admissions, outpatient visits, and prescription medications with varying copayment levels.</p>

  <h2>Lifestyle and Culture</h2>
  <p>Jeddah offers a coastal lifestyle unique in Saudi Arabia. The Corniche provides a 30 km waterfront promenade for walking, cycling, and socializing, with open-air sculpture installations making it an outdoor gallery. Red Sea diving and snorkeling are popular weekend activities, with dive sites accessible from Obhur and boat trips departing from the marina. Al-Balad, the historic city center and UNESCO World Heritage site, features traditional Hejazi architecture with ornate wooden balconies (Rawashin), art galleries, and cafes housed in restored merchant houses. The dining scene is excellent and diverse, reflecting Jeddah's multicultural population, with particularly strong Yemeni, Hejazi, Turkish, and South Asian cuisines alongside international fine dining options along the waterfront.</p>
  <p>Jeddah Season events bring concerts, festivals, and cultural exhibitions, often attracting major international performers. The city hosts regular motorsport events at the Jeddah Corniche Circuit, which has become a fixture on the Formula 1 calendar. Weekend beach trips are a staple of Jeddah social life, with beach resorts and chalets along the coast north of the city offering day passes from SAR 100-300 (~€24-72). For indoor entertainment, the city has modern cinemas, bowling alleys, and family entertainment centers. The food hall at The View mall and the waterfront restaurants at Jeddah Yacht Club are popular gathering spots. Jeddah's proximity to Makkah (80 km) and Madinah (420 km) adds a spiritual dimension for Muslim residents, with Umrah pilgrimages easily accomplished as weekend trips during quieter seasons.</p>

  <h2>Practical Tips for New Arrivals</h2>
  <p>Arriving in Jeddah requires some preparation. Open a bank account at Al Rajhi, SNB, or Riyad Bank within your first week, as your employer will need the details for salary transfer. Get your <a href="/guides/driving-licence/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">driving licence</a> converted or start driving school promptly, as Jeddah is car-dependent. Register with SEC for electricity and NWC for water through their respective apps or offices. Download the Absher app immediately, as it handles residency permit renewals, exit and re-entry visas, and traffic fine payments. For groceries, Danube and Tamimi Markets stock a wide range of international products, while Bin Dawood and Panda offer more budget-friendly options. Join the Jeddah Expats Facebook group and InterNations Jeddah for social networking and community advice. The climate demands adjustment: summer humidity from June to September is intense, and air conditioning is essential. Carry water at all times and schedule outdoor activities for early morning or evening during the hottest months.</p>

